or did he have theological and
philosophical discussions with

00:11:00.934 --> 00:11:03.070
Pilate about his message?
 

00:11:03.070 --> 00:11:04.418
What's historical?
 

00:11:04.418 --> 00:11:08.400
In that case,
basically most historians are

00:11:08.400 --> 00:11:11.149
going to say none of it is.
 

00:11:11.149 --> 00:11:15.070
None of the trial stuff can you
be confident would be

00:11:15.070 --> 00:11:16.048
historical.
 

00:11:16.048 --> 00:11:18.485
For one thing,
we just have these very varied

00:11:18.485 --> 00:11:21.750
differences but there's one very
little interesting piece of

00:11:21.750 --> 00:11:23.080
evidence about this.
 

00:11:23.080 --> 00:11:29.510
According to all the Gospels
where were the disciples after

00:11:29.510 --> 00:11:31.840
Jesus was arrested?
 

00:11:31.840 --> 00:11:33.669
Anybody remember?
 

00:11:33.669 --> 00:11:36.779
They vamoosed.
 

00:11:36.779 --> 00:11:41.230
The Gospels say the disciples
ran away at the arrest of Jesus.

00:11:41.230 --> 00:11:44.787
So maybe according to some
traditions--according to these

00:11:44.787 --> 00:11:48.279
traditions maybe Peter was there
sort of in a courtyard,

00:11:48.279 --> 00:11:50.250
out removed from the trial.
 

00:11:50.250 --> 00:11:54.152
But none of the disciples of
Jesus would have been allowed to

00:11:54.152 --> 00:11:58.119
be present at any trial whether
it was with his high priest or

00:11:58.119 --> 00:12:00.946
Pilate,
they wouldn't have been allowed

00:12:00.946 --> 00:12:01.210
in.
 

00:12:01.210 --> 00:12:03.360
These were peasants from
Galilee, they're fishermen,

00:12:03.360 --> 00:12:06.019
they don't go walking into
Pilate's headquarters,

00:12:06.019 --> 00:12:10.756
so who would have been there to
report these different trial

00:12:10.756 --> 00:12:11.480
things?
 

00:12:11.480 --> 00:12:14.344
There are no stenographers in
the ancient world sitting down

00:12:14.344 --> 00:12:15.850
taking notes of these trials.
 

00:12:15.850 --> 00:12:20.168
There are no court records,
there are no journalists,

00:12:20.168 --> 00:12:24.730
nobody was there who later
Christians had access to so that

00:12:24.730 --> 00:12:29.370
they could possibly have known
what went on in the trial.

00:12:29.370 --> 00:12:32.225
According to most historians
who just say,

00:12:32.225 --> 00:12:35.917
all of this trial stuff was
very much made up by later

00:12:35.917 --> 00:12:36.682
Christians.
 

00:12:36.682 --> 00:12:37.308
Why?
 

00:12:37.308 --> 00:12:40.328
Because they figured you had to
have a trial if you're going to

00:12:40.328 --> 00:12:43.299
have Jesus condemned and so they
figured, well what would have

00:12:43.299 --> 00:12:44.080
taken place?
 

00:12:44.080 --> 00:12:45.788
These Gospel writers,
or maybe they're using

00:12:45.788 --> 00:12:47.418
traditions that developed before
them,

00:12:47.418 --> 00:12:49.873
they're using traditions that
developed because people just

00:12:49.873 --> 00:12:52.615
say,
well what would have happened

00:12:52.615 --> 00:12:54.049
at Jesus' trial?
 

00:12:54.049 --> 00:12:56.048
What's likely to have happened?
 

00:12:56.048 --> 00:12:58.534
Then they make up that
likeliness and they put that

00:12:58.534 --> 00:12:59.379
into the story.
 

00:12:59.379 --> 00:13:03.110
Now so you've got a couple of
different situations where we

00:13:03.110 --> 00:13:06.346
historians are very,
very skeptical about some of

00:13:06.346 --> 00:13:09.860
the basic aspects of the
Gospels' accounts as far as what

00:13:09.860 --> 00:13:12.558
they tell us about the
historical Jesus.

00:13:12.558 --> 00:13:17.129
The birth narratives,
we just throw up our hands.

00:13:17.129 --> 00:13:22.004
The trials before Pilate,
nope probably none of it rises

00:13:22.004 --> 00:13:24.308
to the level of history.
 

00:13:24.308 --> 00:13:27.190
This leads to a couple of
different problems.

00:13:27.190 --> 00:13:30.340
The first one I'm going to talk
about is, so what?

00:13:30.340 --> 00:13:34.264
And I'm saying this because
once critical scholars start

00:13:34.264 --> 00:13:38.190
talking about the historical
Jesus, we immediately start

00:13:38.190 --> 00:13:40.259
stepping into sand traps.
 

00:13:40.259 --> 00:13:45.009
On the one hand we have good
Christian people who are a bit

00:13:45.009 --> 00:13:49.102
afraid that if you start
questioning the historical

00:13:49.102 --> 00:13:54.178
reliability of the Gospels then
you're going to undermine every

00:13:54.178 --> 00:13:56.798
aspect of Christian faith.
 

00:13:56.798 --> 00:14:00.649
If the birth narratives are not
as they say they are in the

00:14:00.649 --> 00:14:04.298
Gospels, then how can you trust
any of it to be true?

00:14:04.298 --> 00:14:07.933
If none of it is true,
how do you even know that Jesus

00:14:07.933 --> 00:14:09.580
actually even existed?
 

00:14:09.580 --> 00:14:14.215
Or even if he did exist how do
you know that he wasn't a liar

00:14:14.215 --> 00:14:16.610
or a magician,
or just a bum?

00:14:16.610 --> 00:14:20.370
How do you--and if that's true,
why have faith?

00:14:20.370 --> 00:14:22.970
Why not just give up the whole
thing?

00:14:22.970 --> 00:14:26.423
On the one hand,
you've got Christians who are

00:14:26.423 --> 00:14:31.260
very threatened by using typical
historical tools on the Gospels

00:14:31.260 --> 00:14:35.100
and the very question of the
historical Jesus.

00:14:35.100 --> 00:14:38.441
On the other hand,
we have just as many people who

00:14:38.441 --> 00:14:42.668
are anti-Christian and they want
to grab onto this and say,

00:14:42.668 --> 00:14:47.178
aha, notice how reputable
scholars like Dale Martin,

00:14:47.178 --> 00:14:50.370
Woolsey Professor or Religious
Studies at Yale University,

00:14:50.370 --> 00:14:53.339
points out that not everything
in the Gospels is reliably

00:14:53.339 --> 00:14:53.870
history.
 

00:14:53.870 --> 00:14:56.533
Well that means it's all a
bunch of bunk,

00:14:56.533 --> 00:15:00.264
and every Christian in the
world is basing their faith on

00:15:00.264 --> 00:15:03.528
things that are known by
scholars to be lies.

00:15:03.528 --> 00:15:07.038
Well that's not exactly right
either is it?

00:15:07.038 --> 00:15:10.230
But on both sides you get some
people who say--

00:15:10.230 --> 00:15:13.575
who grab onto any sort of idea
that historians would say these

00:15:13.575 --> 00:15:15.769
are the discrepancies in the
Gospels,

00:15:15.769 --> 00:15:19.245
or these are places where we
don't have historical evidence

00:15:19.245 --> 00:15:22.961
to back us up and they want to
run with that precisely in order

00:15:22.961 --> 00:15:25.240
to impugn the faith of
Christians.

00:15:25.240 --> 00:15:27.710
So scholars have to be very
careful.

00:15:27.710 --> 00:15:31.123
What we basically want to
say--there was actually one or

00:15:31.123 --> 00:15:33.730
two scholars in the nineteenth
century,

00:15:33.730 --> 00:15:36.279
reputable scholars,
Bruno Bauer was one of them,

00:15:36.279 --> 00:15:39.080
a German scholar who denied
that Jesus ever existed.

00:15:39.080 --> 00:15:41.730
He just said it was all--even
the person of Jesus was a myth

00:15:41.730 --> 00:15:42.808
created by the church.
 

00:15:42.808 --> 00:15:46.379
You'll find every once in a
while somebody on the web,

00:15:46.379 --> 00:15:50.625
or the internet,
or something or in some crazy

00:15:50.625 --> 00:15:52.827
blog,
saying that Jesus never

00:15:52.827 --> 00:15:56.038
existed, but reputable
historical scholars all admit

00:15:56.038 --> 00:15:58.178
that Jesus of Nazareth existed.
 

00:15:58.178 --> 00:16:00.548
There was a guy back there,
Jesus of Nazareth.

00:16:00.548 --> 00:16:03.798
There's just too much evidence
that he existed and it's just

00:16:03.798 --> 00:16:07.490
not controvertible when it comes
to reliable historical evidence.

00:16:07.490 --> 00:16:09.720
That's a big difference from
saying,

00:16:09.720 --> 00:16:11.918
yes, we believe he existed and
there are some things we think

00:16:11.918 --> 00:16:14.649
we can say about him,
to accepting all of the Gospel

00:16:14.649 --> 00:16:16.070
materials as reliable.
 

00:16:16.070 --> 00:16:18.847
Scholars basically are caught
in the middle of saying we

00:16:18.847 --> 00:16:20.918
believe there was a Jesus of
Nazareth,

00:16:20.918 --> 00:16:24.812
we believe we might even be
able to say some things as

00:16:24.812 --> 00:16:27.724
historians about who he was,
what he said,

00:16:27.724 --> 00:16:29.919
what he did,
why he may have been executed,

00:16:29.919 --> 00:16:31.580
and that sort of thing.
 

00:16:31.580 --> 00:16:35.957
That means we have to use
critical historical tools to

00:16:35.957 --> 00:16:40.808
analyze these faith-based texts,
these theological texts,

00:16:40.808 --> 00:16:43.102
what are indeed,
in some cases,

00:16:43.102 --> 00:16:44.279
mythological texts.
 

00:16:44.279 --> 00:16:47.048
We read theological texts to
try to figure out what we could

00:16:47.048 --> 00:16:47.940
say historically.
 

00:16:47.940 --> 00:16:49.908
That leads to the other issue.
 

00:16:49.908 --> 00:16:52.260
I keep saying "the
historical Jesus"

00:16:52.260 --> 00:16:55.344
because a whole lot of people
have the idea that once I give

00:16:55.344 --> 00:16:58.480
you the historical Jesus then
you've got the real Jesus.

00:16:58.480 --> 00:17:02.407
You've got Jesus as he really
was and so therefore Jesus as he

00:17:02.407 --> 00:17:03.178
really is.
 

00:17:03.178 --> 00:17:07.066
Now the problem with that is
that theologians and I can put

00:17:07.066 --> 00:17:11.288
on my historical hat most of the
time, because I actually have a

00:17:11.288 --> 00:17:12.828
job as a historian.
 

00:17:12.828 --> 00:17:15.776
I don't really have a job as a
theologian so I kind of a call

00:17:15.776 --> 00:17:17.788
myself sometimes an amateur
theologian.

00:17:17.788 --> 00:17:20.346
If I want to put on my amateur
theologian hat,

00:17:20.346 --> 00:17:23.642
I can make a case for you why
the historical Jesus is not a

00:17:23.642 --> 00:17:26.200
very good foundation for
Christian faith.

00:17:26.200 --> 00:17:29.002
It's not reliable as a
foundation of Christian faith,

00:17:29.002 --> 00:17:32.130
it's not sufficient as a
foundation for Christian faith.

00:17:32.130 --> 00:17:35.246
The theological Jesus,
the Jesus of Christian

00:17:35.246 --> 00:17:38.150
confession is not the historical
Jesus.

00:17:38.150 --> 00:17:41.701
The Jesus of theological
confession is the Jesus that

00:17:41.701 --> 00:17:45.457
matches what the church has
traditionally believed about

00:17:45.457 --> 00:17:46.140
Jesus.
 

00:17:46.140 --> 00:17:48.440
For example,
Jesus that matches the creeds,

00:17:48.440 --> 00:17:50.750
a Jesus that matches Christian
confessions,

00:17:50.750 --> 00:17:53.308
so one of the most important
things for Christian confession,

00:17:53.308 --> 00:17:55.527
for example,
is--would you lose your faith

00:17:55.527 --> 00:17:58.664
if you believed that Jesus
wasn't born in Bethlehem but was

00:17:58.664 --> 00:18:00.180
rather born in Nazareth?
 

00:18:00.180 --> 00:18:03.621
Probably most Christians would
say, well, no that's not really

00:18:03.621 --> 00:18:04.578
that important.
 

00:18:04.578 --> 00:18:07.231
What's the most central thing
for most Christians of the

00:18:07.231 --> 00:18:08.098
Christian faith?
 

00:18:08.098 --> 00:18:12.151
Do you believe that somehow God
was in Jesus Christ reconciling

00:18:12.151 --> 00:18:15.401
the world to himself,
to quote the Apostle Paul,

00:18:15.401 --> 00:18:18.440
or do you believe that Jesus
Christ is divine?

00:18:18.440 --> 00:18:20.259
Do you believe that Jesus is
God?

00:18:20.259 --> 00:18:22.711
Do you believe that Jesus is
God incarnate,

00:18:22.711 --> 00:18:23.818
God in the flesh?
 

00:18:23.818 --> 00:18:27.010
That's a fundamental aspect of
Christian faith for most

00:18:27.010 --> 00:18:27.778
Christians.
 

00:18:27.778 --> 00:18:30.890
Notice that's not something
that historians can pronounce

00:18:30.890 --> 00:18:32.390
about one way or another.
 

00:18:32.390 --> 00:18:36.502
There's no possible way that I
practicing history by the normal

00:18:36.502 --> 00:18:40.218
historiographical tools of
history could tell you whether

00:18:40.218 --> 00:18:42.740
God was in Jesus Christ,
is there?

00:18:42.740 --> 00:18:44.430
I mean just think about it,
how would I test that?

00:18:44.430 --> 00:18:46.828
How would I figure it out?
 

00:18:46.828 --> 00:18:49.400
What would count as a positive
proof?

00:18:49.400 --> 00:18:52.098
What would count as a
non-controvertible negative

00:18:52.098 --> 00:18:52.549
truth?
 

00:18:52.549 --> 00:18:53.720
There's no such thing.
 

00:18:53.720 --> 00:18:57.604
When I'm talking about the
historical Jesus I have to get

00:18:57.604 --> 00:18:59.200
over several hurdles.
 

00:18:59.200 --> 00:19:03.106
One of the hurdles is trying to
show you that the historical

00:19:03.106 --> 00:19:06.816
Jesus is a construction made by
historians practicing the

00:19:06.816 --> 00:19:09.400
typical trade of modern
historians.

00:19:09.400 --> 00:19:11.125
It's just like,
for example,

00:19:11.125 --> 00:19:13.808
if I say what's the historical
Socrates?

00:19:13.808 --> 00:19:17.353
We don't have direct access to
Socrates either,

00:19:17.353 --> 00:19:17.970
right?
 

00:19:17.970 --> 00:19:19.568
Socrates left no writings.
 

00:19:19.568 --> 00:19:23.439
All we know about Socrates are
mainly the things that either

00:19:23.439 --> 00:19:24.721
Plato,
his disciple,

00:19:24.721 --> 00:19:27.652
said about him or Xenophon
another of his disciples said

00:19:27.652 --> 00:19:29.569
about him and a few other
things.

00:19:29.569 --> 00:19:31.798
You know what?
 

00:19:31.798 --> 00:19:34.538
Plato and Xenophon don't give
the same picture of Socrates,

00:19:34.538 --> 00:19:38.000
so figuring out what this--who
is the historical Socrates is

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:41.403
also a difficult historical
question that historians debate

00:19:41.403 --> 00:19:41.990
about.
 

00:19:41.990 --> 00:19:45.670
That's the one thing is just
using typical historical data.

00:19:45.670 --> 00:19:47.854
For example,
if I say, we're going to talk

00:19:47.854 --> 00:19:50.837
about George Washington and
we're going to talk about the

00:19:50.837 --> 00:19:53.483
George Washington of history,
the George Washington that

00:19:53.483 --> 00:19:55.980
historians will come up with,
that's a different George

00:19:55.980 --> 00:19:58.972
Washington than say,
let's talk about the George

00:19:58.972 --> 00:20:01.328
Washington of popular American
piety.

00:20:01.328 --> 00:20:04.378
The George Washington of
popular American piety threw a

00:20:04.378 --> 00:20:05.960
dollar across the Potomac.
 

00:20:05.960 --> 00:20:09.590
No historian believes that
George Washington threw a dollar

00:20:09.590 --> 00:20:11.971
across the Potomac,
at least not at Mt.

00:20:11.971 --> 00:20:12.660
Vernon.
 

00:20:12.660 --> 00:20:14.224
If you've been to Mt.
 

00:20:14.224 --> 00:20:17.430
Vernon you know that's a super
human feat.

00:20:17.430 --> 00:20:20.046
In popular American piety,
George Washington as a little

00:20:20.046 --> 00:20:23.090
boy chopped down the cherry tree
and when his father got onto him

00:20:23.090 --> 00:20:25.358
he said,
I cannot tell a lie father,

00:20:25.358 --> 00:20:25.910
it is I.
 

00:20:25.910 --> 00:20:28.930
That's a George Washington,
it's the George Washington of

00:20:28.930 --> 00:20:32.058
American popular tradition,
and it's important to know that

00:20:32.058 --> 00:20:33.568
about George Washington.
 

00:20:33.568 --> 00:20:36.188
No historian believes that
George Washington as a child

00:20:36.188 --> 00:20:39.048
actually chopped down the cherry
tree and that happened,

00:20:39.048 --> 00:20:42.000
and mainly because we actually
found the preacher who made up

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:43.230
the story for a sermon.
 

00:20:43.230 --> 00:20:47.000
It made a good sermon point.
 

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:50.838
Remember my motto,
what's the motto of the class?

00:20:50.838 --> 00:20:55.253
De omnibus dubitandum,
especially when you're

00:20:55.253 --> 00:20:58.630
listening to preachers or
professors.

00:20:58.630 --> 00:21:02.953
The historical Jesus is not the
same thing as the theological

00:21:02.953 --> 00:21:05.910
Jesus, so that's one point to
remember.

00:21:05.910 --> 00:21:08.678
Another--this is another
theoretical issue and this is

00:21:08.678 --> 00:21:11.759
very confusing for some people
when you first start thinking

00:21:11.759 --> 00:21:12.440
about it.
 

00:21:12.440 --> 00:21:16.878
We often use the word
"history"

00:21:16.878 --> 00:21:21.538
in two different ways in common
English.

00:21:21.538 --> 00:21:27.118
We often use the word history
to refer simply to stuff in the

00:21:27.118 --> 00:21:27.769
past.
 

00:21:27.769 --> 00:21:33.759
For example,
the Civil War is historical.

00:21:33.759 --> 00:21:36.410
That just means it happened in
the past.

00:21:36.410 --> 00:21:38.972
That's one way we use the word
"history"

00:21:38.972 --> 00:21:42.821
but it's kind of a sloppy way,
because if I want to say the

00:21:42.821 --> 00:21:47.229
history of the Civil War,
I'm not really talking in that

00:21:47.229 --> 00:21:50.058
case of the whole Civil War,
right?

00:21:50.058 --> 00:21:53.640
A historical account of the
Civil War is something--

00:21:53.640 --> 00:21:57.742
is a narrative that will be
constructed by a historian to

00:21:57.742 --> 00:22:01.920
represent a story about whatever
happened in the past,

00:22:01.920 --> 00:22:04.558
but it can't replicate the
past, right?

00:22:04.558 --> 00:22:09.705
In order to replicate the Civil
War you would have to actually

00:22:09.705 --> 00:22:13.838
have the full four years--wasn't
it four years?

00:22:13.838 --> 00:22:17.452
However long the Civil War took
to fight you would have to have

00:22:17.452 --> 00:22:20.308
that amount of time because
every tiny detail,

00:22:20.308 --> 00:22:21.855
every action,
every person,

00:22:21.855 --> 00:22:23.246
every word,
every letter,

00:22:23.246 --> 00:22:25.991
everything anybody said all--
every tiny battle,

00:22:25.991 --> 00:22:30.703
every ant that crawled over a
decomposing corpse is part of

00:22:30.703 --> 00:22:33.058
the past of the Civil War.
 

00:22:33.058 --> 00:22:37.940
That's not the history of the
Civil War, that's the Civil War

00:22:37.940 --> 00:22:40.298
as it occurred in the past.
 

00:22:40.298 --> 00:22:43.959
The history of the Civil War is
an account of whatever happened

00:22:43.959 --> 00:22:47.558
in the past that a historian
constructs and then tells you.

00:22:47.558 --> 00:22:49.329
When we use the word
"history"

00:22:49.329 --> 00:22:50.920
in that more professional
sense,

00:22:50.920 --> 00:22:54.211
we're not talking about the
past, we're talking about an

00:22:54.211 --> 00:22:55.529
account of the past.
 

00:22:55.529 --> 00:22:59.997
Often philosophers of history
like to separate these two words

00:22:59.997 --> 00:23:01.865
out,
and they'll use the word

00:23:01.865 --> 00:23:04.461
"past"
for the event that occurred in

00:23:04.461 --> 00:23:05.140
the past.
 

00:23:05.140 --> 00:23:07.430
They'll use the word
"history"

00:23:07.430 --> 00:23:10.720
for an account of the event
that occurred in the past.

00:23:10.720 --> 00:23:12.730
Now notice what that means.
 

00:23:12.730 --> 00:23:15.348
Histories are accessible to us,
right?

00:23:15.348 --> 00:23:18.679
You can go to the store and buy
a history of the Civil War,

00:23:18.679 --> 00:23:22.122
you can buy a history of George
Washington, and you can buy a

00:23:22.122 --> 00:23:23.730
history of Jesus Christ.
 

00:23:23.730 --> 00:23:27.678
Does the history of the Civil
War that you buy in the store

00:23:27.678 --> 00:23:29.380
give you the Civil War?
 

00:23:29.380 --> 00:23:33.779
No, it gives you an account of
the Civil War.

00:23:33.779 --> 00:23:37.990
The actual Civil War is
radically inaccessible to you.

00:23:37.990 --> 00:23:39.798
It's inaccessible,
you can't get it.

00:23:39.798 --> 00:23:44.402
Think about this,
how would you actually recover

00:23:44.402 --> 00:23:47.829
