00:36:26.925 --> 00:36:27.889
the other details later.
 

00:36:27.889 --> 00:36:30.429
Right now let's talk about
method, how did I get here?

00:36:30.429 --> 00:36:32.385
First method,
first little rule,

00:36:32.385 --> 00:36:36.045
and this is something that a
lot of people use when they do

00:36:36.045 --> 00:36:37.940
historical Jesus research.
 

00:36:37.940 --> 00:36:40.596
It took all of the twentieth
century for people kind of to

00:36:40.596 --> 00:36:43.577
develop these rules and to spell
them out in scholarship but this

00:36:43.577 --> 00:36:45.070
is kind of where we are now.
 

00:36:45.070 --> 00:36:47.460
The first rule,
multiple attestation,

00:36:55.510 --> 00:36:59.949
that means when you have more
than one independent source that

00:36:59.949 --> 00:37:02.860
has a saying or an event about
Jesus,

00:37:02.860 --> 00:37:05.480
you tend to give it a little
more weight.

00:37:05.480 --> 00:37:08.869
Now of course what are
independent sources?

00:37:08.869 --> 00:37:12.193
If you have something in both
Matthew and Luke that doesn't

00:37:12.193 --> 00:37:14.599
count as two independent
sources, right?

00:37:14.599 --> 00:37:16.820
Because both Matthew and Luke
could have gotten it from Mark

00:37:16.820 --> 00:37:18.289
or they could have gotten it
from Q,

00:37:18.289 --> 00:37:23.114
but if you have something in
Mark and you have something in

00:37:23.114 --> 00:37:25.079
John,
well those are two independent

00:37:25.079 --> 00:37:25.469
sources.
 

00:37:25.469 --> 00:37:28.291
If you also have something in
the Gospel of Thomas then most

00:37:28.291 --> 00:37:30.931
of us scholars would say,
well some people say the Gospel

00:37:30.931 --> 00:37:32.820
of Thomas may have known the
other Gospels,

00:37:32.820 --> 00:37:35.346
but most of us would say,
we're going to treat him as an

00:37:35.346 --> 00:37:38.148
independent source because he's
not verbatim quoting the other

00:37:38.148 --> 00:37:39.480
Gospels most of the time.
 

00:37:39.480 --> 00:37:43.192
If you have an event or a
saying that occurs in Mark and

00:37:43.192 --> 00:37:46.635
John, and Q, and Thomas those
are three [correction:

00:37:46.635 --> 00:37:48.659
four]
independent sources.

00:37:48.659 --> 00:37:51.010
What if it also occurs in Paul,
Paul's letters?

00:37:51.010 --> 00:37:52.010
There's another independent
source.

00:37:52.010 --> 00:37:55.373
As we'll see there are some
places where Paul gives us a

00:37:55.373 --> 00:37:57.210
little clue about something.
 

00:37:57.210 --> 00:38:00.579
Then obviously you can take Q
as being one of those sources,

00:38:00.579 --> 00:38:03.809
so if something is in both
Matthew and Luke but it's not in

00:38:03.809 --> 00:38:07.463
Mark then you can say it's in Q,
and sometimes people would even

00:38:07.463 --> 00:38:10.978
say you have one form of parable
that seems to have occurred in Q

00:38:10.978 --> 00:38:14.440
and you have a different form of
that parable that seems to have

00:38:14.440 --> 00:38:15.650
occurred in Mark.
 

00:38:15.650 --> 00:38:18.626
Then you can say,
okay we have this one parable

00:38:18.626 --> 00:38:21.942
in two independent sources,
one is Q and one is Mark,

00:38:21.942 --> 00:38:25.014
but that's kind of complicated
because of course the very

00:38:25.014 --> 00:38:28.307
definition of what's in Q is
something that's in both Matthew

00:38:28.307 --> 00:38:30.860
and Luke but not in Mark,
usually.

00:38:30.860 --> 00:38:34.413
If something is in more than
one source it fits this

00:38:34.413 --> 00:38:35.250
criterion.
 

00:38:35.250 --> 00:38:39.862
Now remember criteria is the
plural, criterion is the

00:38:39.862 --> 00:38:40.840
singular.
 

00:38:48.199 --> 00:38:50.630
Let me illustrate this again.
 

00:38:50.630 --> 00:38:53.514
One of the things is the sign
on the cross,

00:38:53.514 --> 00:38:56.469
the divorce sayings is another
situation.

00:38:56.469 --> 00:39:00.699
According to Mark 10 and
Matthew 19 you have this saying,

00:39:00.699 --> 00:39:03.253
"What God has joined
together let no man put

00:39:03.253 --> 00:39:05.541
asunder,"
and then you have a few other

00:39:05.541 --> 00:39:06.179
sayings.
 

00:39:06.179 --> 00:39:07.860
Clearly Jesus,
in this passage,

00:39:07.860 --> 00:39:11.164
is teaching no divorce for his
disciples, no divorce at all,

00:39:11.164 --> 00:39:13.179
period, none,
against the rule to get

00:39:13.179 --> 00:39:14.018
divorced.
 

00:39:14.018 --> 00:39:17.960
Then Matthew 5:32 has a
parallel with Luke 16:18 which

00:39:17.960 --> 00:39:22.349
makes it look like a Q source
and that has this wording,

00:39:22.349 --> 00:39:25.150
"Every man who divorces
his wife and marries another

00:39:25.150 --> 00:39:27.628
commits adultery,
and whoever marries a woman who

00:39:27.628 --> 00:39:30.349
has been divorced by her husband
commits adultery."

00:39:30.349 --> 00:39:31.920
In other words,
there's another teaching on

00:39:31.920 --> 00:39:33.931
divorce here,
both of which forbid--it also

00:39:33.931 --> 00:39:37.237
forbids divorce and remarriage,
but it's not the same wording

00:39:37.237 --> 00:39:38.942
as in Mark,
so scholars say,

00:39:38.942 --> 00:39:42.300
that looks like a Q saying on
divorce in which Jesus still

00:39:42.300 --> 00:39:45.952
forbids divorce and remarriage
but it's not the same wording as

00:39:45.952 --> 00:39:49.469
the Mark saying,
so we have two separate sayings

00:39:49.469 --> 00:39:52.369
and different wordings,
but they both have Jesus

00:39:52.369 --> 00:39:55.719
forbidding divorce,
at least divorce and remarriage;

00:39:55.719 --> 00:39:58.989
one in Q, one in Mark,
two independent sources.

00:39:58.989 --> 00:40:03.237
It's really neat then when we
find Paul in 1 Corinthians

00:40:03.237 --> 00:40:05.956
7:10-11 says this,
so this is Paul,

00:40:05.956 --> 00:40:09.172
a quotation from Paul,
"To those who are married

00:40:09.172 --> 00:40:11.739
I command,"
that is Paul and then he says,

00:40:11.739 --> 00:40:13.670
"Not I but the Lord."
 

00:40:13.670 --> 00:40:18.518
Paul even knows he's quoting a
saying of the Lord Jesus,

00:40:18.518 --> 00:40:20.567
so he goes onto say,
"That the woman must not

00:40:20.567 --> 00:40:23.260
separate from her husband,
if indeed she does separate let

00:40:23.260 --> 00:40:25.889
her remain unmarried or be
reconciled to her husband,

00:40:25.889 --> 00:40:28.110
and a man must not put away his
wife."

00:40:28.110 --> 00:40:30.510
Now most of us believe that's
Paul's wording because you can

00:40:30.510 --> 00:40:32.791
tell the way he's kind of
fudging around with some of the

00:40:32.791 --> 00:40:33.849
details of the saying.
 

00:40:33.849 --> 00:40:38.286
At least Paul gives a witness
that he knows of an anti-divorce

00:40:38.286 --> 00:40:39.960
saying by Jesus also.
 

00:40:39.960 --> 00:40:44.885
Three separate independent
witnesses that Jesus taught

00:40:44.885 --> 00:40:46.559
against divorce.
 

00:40:46.559 --> 00:40:51.170
One from Mark that Matthew
copies, one from Q that both

00:40:51.170 --> 00:40:54.585
Matthew and Luke have,
and one from Paul,

00:40:54.585 --> 00:40:58.768
so that passes the multiple
attestation rule.

00:40:58.768 --> 00:41:02.829
It also passes the next rule,
which is dissimilarity.

00:41:07.889 --> 00:41:10.320
When you find something in a
source,

00:41:10.320 --> 00:41:13.909
the early Christian source,
that seems to go against the

00:41:13.909 --> 00:41:16.260
very inclinations of that
source,

00:41:16.260 --> 00:41:19.791
or of early Christianity,
it's more likely to be

00:41:19.791 --> 00:41:20.768
historical.
 

00:41:20.768 --> 00:41:25.025
Something that swims against
the tide of early Christian

00:41:25.025 --> 00:41:26.110
expectation.
 

00:41:26.110 --> 00:41:29.230
Now why does the--divorce
saying is multiply attest--

00:41:29.230 --> 00:41:31.757
it also passes the
dissimilarity thing because

00:41:31.757 --> 00:41:34.356
almost all of these authors,
except for Mark,

00:41:34.356 --> 00:41:37.083
they both seem to know that
Jesus prohibited divorce

00:41:37.083 --> 00:41:40.402
entirely but then they go on to
modify the rule a bit because I

00:41:40.402 --> 00:41:42.809
mean let's face it people get
divorced,

00:41:42.809 --> 00:41:44.739
early Christians got divorced.
 

00:41:44.739 --> 00:41:46.882
So Paul says,
well you're not supposed to get

00:41:46.882 --> 00:41:49.510
divorced, but if you do get
divorced then you should do

00:41:49.510 --> 00:41:49.949
this.
 

00:41:49.949 --> 00:41:55.300
The very writers who pass on an
anti-divorce saying also fudged

00:41:55.300 --> 00:41:59.405
the saying just a bit,
which shows that the saying is

00:41:59.405 --> 00:42:02.000
more radical than their own
ethics are.

00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:04.492
In other words,
the anti-divorce saying is

00:42:04.492 --> 00:42:08.199
dissimilar to the very practices
of these early Christians.

00:42:08.199 --> 00:42:11.514
It's more radical then they are
themselves practicing and that's

00:42:11.514 --> 00:42:14.460
a clue that the saying itself
goes back to the historical

00:42:14.460 --> 00:42:16.949
Jesus,
according to this method.

00:42:16.949 --> 00:42:21.556
Dissimilarity is any kind of
thing that doesn't fit early

00:42:21.556 --> 00:42:23.449
Christian tendencies.
 

00:42:23.449 --> 00:42:25.353
The sign on the cross,
I already talked about that,

00:42:25.353 --> 00:42:26.650
it wasn't a confession of
Jesus.

00:42:26.650 --> 00:42:29.190
The baptism of John,
it's not something they likely

00:42:29.190 --> 00:42:30.309
would have invented.
 

00:42:30.309 --> 00:42:33.250
There's another one,
the swords at Jesus' arrest,

00:42:33.250 --> 00:42:36.956
and according to Mark 14:47 and
it's followed by Matthew and

00:42:36.956 --> 00:42:39.621
Luke,
somebody had a sword at Jesus'

00:42:39.621 --> 00:42:43.429
arrest in the garden,
and somebody used it.

00:42:43.429 --> 00:42:45.719
According to the different
traditions it was Peter,

00:42:45.719 --> 00:42:47.789
according to John and somebody
made--

00:42:47.789 --> 00:42:50.780
the others don't name,
somebody whacked off the high--

00:42:50.780 --> 00:42:52.719
the ear of the high priest's
slave,

00:42:52.719 --> 00:42:57.077
but there are these different
stories about somebody in Jesus'

00:42:57.077 --> 00:43:00.650
entourage was armed and in some
of the sources--

00:43:00.650 --> 00:43:02.239
one of the sources there are
two of them--

00:43:02.239 --> 00:43:04.500
or there were two
swords--others say one sword.

00:43:04.500 --> 00:43:07.090
Now I think this is historical.
 

00:43:07.090 --> 00:43:07.510
Why?
 

00:43:07.510 --> 00:43:10.710
Because all the Gospel writers
want to go out of their way to

00:43:10.710 --> 00:43:13.380
say Jesus was not mounting a
violent revolution.

00:43:13.380 --> 00:43:15.969
He was not a criminal,
this was not an armed

00:43:15.969 --> 00:43:19.525
rebellion, he is completely
innocent of any political charge

00:43:19.525 --> 00:43:20.730
of insurrection.
 

00:43:20.730 --> 00:43:25.056
But if Jesus' disciples were
armed with swords at his arrest,

00:43:25.056 --> 00:43:29.094
in the middle of the night,
at the Passover in Jerusalem,

00:43:29.094 --> 00:43:31.329
that's insurrection,
folks.

00:43:31.329 --> 00:43:35.146
The Romans did not allow Jews
just to go around in the middle

00:43:35.146 --> 00:43:37.820
of the night in gardens carrying
swords.

00:43:37.820 --> 00:43:41.030
For a Jew to be armed,
at the Passover,

00:43:41.030 --> 00:43:44.005
an especially dangerous time,
that the Romans were really

00:43:44.005 --> 00:43:46.438
worried about,
for a Jew to be armed following

00:43:46.438 --> 00:43:49.346
around a guy who some people
were saying was the King of the

00:43:49.346 --> 00:43:52.259
Jews,
you can be arrested for that,

00:43:52.259 --> 00:43:54.900
you can be crucified for that.
 

00:43:54.900 --> 00:43:58.179
I don't think early Christians
invented it.

00:43:58.179 --> 00:44:02.255
I think some of these early
Christians knew that at least

00:44:02.255 --> 00:44:06.478
one and possibly more of Jesus'
disciples were armed at his

00:44:06.478 --> 00:44:07.280
arrest.
 

00:44:07.280 --> 00:44:08.590
Why do I think that?
 

00:44:08.590 --> 00:44:09.780
Because it's not something they
would have invented.

00:44:09.780 --> 00:44:11.789
In fact, it goes against their
tendency.

00:44:11.789 --> 00:44:17.726
There's another passage,
Mark 10:18 which is also in

00:44:17.726 --> 00:44:19.239
Luke 18:19.
 

00:44:19.239 --> 00:44:22.260
You may have come across this,
the man comes and asks Jesus

00:44:22.260 --> 00:44:24.710
about what should I do to have
eternal life,

00:44:24.710 --> 00:44:25.909
what's the good thing for me to
do,

00:44:25.909 --> 00:44:28.697
and Jesus says,
why do you ask me about the

00:44:28.697 --> 00:44:33.239
good,
there's no one good but God.

00:44:33.239 --> 00:44:37.429
Now, apparently,
Mark writing that didn't have a

00:44:37.429 --> 00:44:42.869
theological hiccup but now let
me--I'm a good Episcopalian.

00:44:42.869 --> 00:44:48.556
Why should you ask Jesus about
the good, God's the only who is

00:44:48.556 --> 00:44:49.210
good.
 

00:44:49.210 --> 00:44:51.920
Sound weird?
 

00:44:51.920 --> 00:44:57.190
If Jesus is actually God then
you wouldn't say it like that.

00:44:57.190 --> 00:45:01.389
In other words,
this sounds like Jesus himself

00:45:01.389 --> 00:45:03.909
is denying that he's God.
 

00:45:03.909 --> 00:45:07.552
Don't ask me about the good,
the only one who knows about

00:45:07.552 --> 00:45:11.130
good is God, and Jesus goes and
answers the question.

00:45:11.130 --> 00:45:14.735
I think this saying was
actually--something like this

00:45:14.735 --> 00:45:16.954
was said by the historical
Jesus.

00:45:16.954 --> 00:45:17.510
Why?
 

00:45:17.510 --> 00:45:20.905
Because early followers of
Jesus believed Jesus was God in

00:45:20.905 --> 00:45:21.679
some sense.
 

00:45:21.679 --> 00:45:24.429
I don't think this is something
they would invent.

00:45:24.429 --> 00:45:27.300
It goes against their
confession.

00:45:27.300 --> 00:45:31.143
It goes against their theology,
so it's one of these cases

00:45:31.143 --> 00:45:33.840
where it's dissimilar to their
faith,

00:45:33.840 --> 00:45:38.123
and therefore,
we tend to give it a higher

00:45:38.123 --> 00:45:41.989
grade when it comes to
historicity.

00:45:41.989 --> 00:45:45.300
A couple of other criteria are
a bit weaker,

00:45:45.300 --> 00:45:47.610
these are the two strongest.
 

00:45:47.610 --> 00:45:52.219
Social coherence.
 

00:45:52.219 --> 00:45:55.646
This is when you say--when you
use something that is either

00:45:55.646 --> 00:45:59.072
anachronistic and it doesn't
look like it would fit in with

00:45:59.072 --> 00:46:02.500
the life of Jesus or it does fit
very well with the life of

00:46:02.500 --> 00:46:03.210
Jesus.
 

00:46:03.210 --> 00:46:04.259
If I decide,
for example,

00:46:04.259 --> 00:46:06.664
on lots of different other
sayings that I've decided are

00:46:06.664 --> 00:46:08.719
historical because of these
other reasons,

00:46:08.719 --> 00:46:11.286
and then something looks like
it--a saying of Jesus looks like

00:46:11.286 --> 00:46:13.601
it's apocalyptic and I've
already established that Jesus

00:46:13.601 --> 00:46:16.811
was an apocalyptic prophet,
then I'm going to say well it

00:46:16.811 --> 00:46:19.827
coheres with the social
situation of Jesus as an

00:46:19.827 --> 00:46:22.010
apocalyptic prophet in Galilee.
 

00:46:22.010 --> 00:46:25.594
Or take a negative example,
in Matthew 18 there are a lot

00:46:25.594 --> 00:46:28.860
of rules about what you should
do in the church,

00:46:28.860 --> 00:46:30.356
the very word
"church"

00:46:30.356 --> 00:46:30.840
is used.
 

00:46:30.840 --> 00:46:33.760
Almost all of us scholars would
say a lot of that stuff in

00:46:33.760 --> 00:46:35.983
Matthew 18 about the church,
the church rules,

00:46:35.983 --> 00:46:39.320
the church leadership,
that's not historical. Why?

00:46:39.320 --> 00:46:42.039
Because the church didn't exist
in Jesus' lifetime.

00:46:42.039 --> 00:46:45.992
Jesus sounds like he's giving
rules about a constitution for a

00:46:45.992 --> 00:46:48.780
church but we think that's
anachronistic.

00:46:48.780 --> 00:46:51.817
The church is something that
developed after Jesus' death

00:46:51.817 --> 00:46:54.909
when his followers came to
believe that he had been raised

00:46:54.909 --> 00:46:58.056
from the dead and then they
should continue doing things in

00:46:58.056 --> 00:46:58.869
his name.
 

00:46:58.869 --> 00:47:01.659
In Jesus' own lifetime,
traveling around Galilee,

00:47:01.659 --> 00:47:04.148
talking about--now when you
have the church you should meet

00:47:04.148 --> 00:47:06.364
on Sundays,
I think for Easter you should

00:47:06.364 --> 00:47:11.369
wear white--
Jesus didn't do this sort of

00:47:11.369 --> 00:47:12.440
thing.
 

00:47:12.440 --> 00:47:16.393
All of that stuff in Matthew 18
that looks very much like later

00:47:16.393 --> 00:47:19.233
church life,
we believe was read back into

00:47:19.233 --> 00:47:23.130
the life of Jesus by the author
of Matthew or other people.

00:47:23.130 --> 00:47:26.907
Then the last thing is,
the last criterion is rather

00:47:26.907 --> 00:47:30.389
weak, it's called the criterion
of coherence.

00:47:30.389 --> 00:47:33.989
This basically just says,
if you've established something

00:47:33.989 --> 00:47:37.460
as being historical about Jesus
by these other stronger

00:47:37.460 --> 00:47:39.844
criteria,
and then something else seems

00:47:39.844 --> 00:47:42.474
to cohere with it,
then you can kind of throw it

00:47:42.474 --> 00:47:43.139
in the pot.
 

00:47:43.139 --> 00:47:48.514
It's a very loose kind of
criterion to use for historical

00:47:48.514 --> 00:47:49.570
purposes.
 

00:47:49.570 --> 00:47:51.400
Now--so where are we?
 

00:47:51.400 --> 00:47:53.280
That's the methodology.
 

00:47:53.280 --> 00:47:55.974
If we're going to come up with
some basic ideas about Jesus

00:47:55.974 --> 00:47:58.159
here's where I would say I would
end up with.

00:47:58.159 --> 00:48:01.030
There's some of this that's
very controversial.

00:48:01.030 --> 00:48:03.302
I would say,
though, that Jesus was an

00:48:03.302 --> 00:48:06.559
apocalyptic prophet,
an apocalyptic Jewish prophet.

00:48:06.559 --> 00:48:10.141
One of the reasons is that
Jesus' life was framed by two

00:48:10.141 --> 00:48:11.510
apocalyptic events.
 

00:48:11.510 --> 00:48:14.139
If Jesus was baptized by John
the Baptist,

00:48:14.139 --> 00:48:16.748
and John the Baptist seems
clearly to have been preaching

00:48:16.748 --> 00:48:19.590
some kind of apocalyptic message
about the coming kingdom,

00:48:19.590 --> 00:48:22.096
that means I think,
that Jesus was originally a

00:48:22.096 --> 00:48:24.927
follower of John the Baptist,
although the later Gospel

00:48:24.927 --> 00:48:26.190
writers will play that down.
 

00:48:26.190 --> 00:48:29.650
If Jesus was a follower of an
apocalyptic Jewish prophet I

00:48:29.650 --> 00:48:32.443
think that,
at least the beginning of his

00:48:32.443 --> 00:48:34.793
own ministry,
was wreathed in that

00:48:34.793 --> 00:48:37.750
apocalyptic Jewish prophecy kind
of world,

00:48:37.750 --> 00:48:43.025
and he was executed on a charge
of sedition as being the King of

00:48:43.025 --> 00:48:45.449
the Jews,
against the law.

00:48:45.449 --> 00:48:47.929
Only the Roman senate got to
make kings,

00:48:47.929 --> 00:48:50.550
and if Jesus was going around
claiming--

00:48:50.550 --> 00:48:51.920
and I'm not saying he was
claiming,

00:48:51.920 --> 00:48:54.275
but if other people were
claiming that he was the King of

00:48:54.275 --> 00:48:56.387
the Jews,
the only way to understand that

00:48:56.387 --> 00:48:59.295
I think in this situation is
that he believed that he was

00:48:59.295 --> 00:49:02.253
going to be the Messiah that
would come at the end of time

00:49:02.253 --> 00:49:03.809
and overthrow the Romans.
 

00:49:03.809 --> 00:49:07.469
So his death was also
apocalyptic.

00:49:07.469 --> 00:49:09.539
The temple incident,
we could talk about that,

00:49:09.539 --> 00:49:12.253
did Jesus go in and throw the
money changers out and cleanse

00:49:12.253 --> 00:49:13.449
the temple as it said?
 

00:49:13.449 --> 00:49:14.590
I think that's historical.
 

00:49:14.590 --> 00:49:18.117
It goes against the tendency of
the Gospels to portray Jesus as

00:49:18.117 --> 00:49:20.849
violent and confrontational in
that last week.

00:49:20.849 --> 00:49:22.969
I think he therefore did it.
 

00:49:22.969 --> 00:49:24.090
What did it mean?
 

00:49:24.090 --> 00:49:25.659
I think it--this is more
debatable,

00:49:25.659 --> 00:49:29.079
I think it was a prophecy meant
to enact what he saw would be

00:49:29.079 --> 00:49:32.670
the coming future destruction of
the temple by God and some kind

00:49:32.670 --> 00:49:35.179
of apocalyptic event at the end
of time.

00:49:35.179 --> 00:49:40.769
I think Jesus was therefore a
lower class Jewish peasant who

00:49:40.769 --> 00:49:42.949
spoke mainly Aramaic.
 

00:49:42.949 --> 00:49:46.429
I think he had a group of
disciples of twelve,

00:49:46.429 --> 00:49:49.440
I won't go into some of these,
but I think he actually did

00:49:49.440 --> 00:49:52.449
form twelve of his disciples to
be an inner core group.

00:49:52.449 --> 00:49:54.170
I think even that's apocalyptic.
 

00:49:54.170 --> 00:49:56.199
Why would he have twelve
disciples?

00:49:56.199 --> 00:49:57.570
Why did he choose the number
twelve?

00:49:57.570 --> 00:50:00.418
Because there were twelve
tribes of Israel that would be

00:50:00.418 --> 00:50:03.889
reconstituted at the end of time
according to Jewish expectation.

00:50:03.889 --> 00:50:07.646
I think there are also women
that were part of his inner

00:50:07.646 --> 00:50:09.800
circle,
and this is because women later

00:50:09.800 --> 00:50:12.364
in early Christianity were
marginalized from leadership

00:50:12.364 --> 00:50:14.239
positions,
but there's all kinds of

00:50:14.239 --> 00:50:16.460
evidence from the resurrection
narratives,

00:50:16.460 --> 00:50:19.057
to the presence of Mary
Magdalene, to other women that

00:50:19.057 --> 00:50:21.510
they were part of his inner
circle of disciples.

00:50:21.510 --> 00:50:25.016
I think that he never taught
the end of the Jewish law but I

00:50:25.016 --> 00:50:28.226
think he did teach what was
something of a liberalizing

00:50:28.226 --> 00:50:30.010
version of the Jewish law.
 

00:50:30.010 --> 00:50:33.324
In other words,
that the ethical treatment of

00:50:33.324 --> 00:50:37.920
your fellow human beings counted
as more important than actual

00:50:37.920 --> 00:50:41.010
details of observing the Jewish
law,

00:50:41.010 --> 00:50:43.559
such as keeping kosher,
washing your hands,

00:50:43.559 --> 00:50:45.070
keeping the Sabbath.
 

00:50:45.070 --> 00:50:48.190
Did Jesus think he was the
Messiah?

00:50:48.190 --> 00:50:50.409
I think this is a really big
problem.

00:50:50.409 --> 00:50:51.429
I don't know.
 

00:50:51.429 --> 00:50:54.963
There seem to be places where
he makes no open claim to

00:50:54.963 --> 00:50:58.628
Messiahship in his ministry,
except in the Gospel of John

00:50:58.628 --> 00:50:59.480
remember.
 

00:50:59.480 --> 00:51:02.143
So the Gospel of John actually
we tend to treat that as less

00:51:02.143 --> 00:51:04.762
historically reliable in these
things because it looks very

00:51:04.762 --> 00:51:07.110
much more like Christian
theological confession.

00:51:07.110 --> 00:51:11.583
In the Synoptic Gospels,
Jesus doesn't make open claims

00:51:11.583 --> 00:51:13.489
to being the Messiah.
 

00:51:13.489 --> 00:51:16.237
On the other hand,
he was executed for being King

00:51:16.237 --> 00:51:17.039
of the Jews.
 

00:51:17.039 --> 00:51:20.501
The Romans at least thought he
was claiming to be the Messiah,

00:51:20.501 --> 00:51:23.735
or they thought that other
people were claiming that about

00:51:23.735 --> 00:51:24.190
him.
 

00:51:24.190 --> 00:51:27.460
What he thought himself is very
difficult.

00:51:27.460 --> 00:51:29.684
One of the things,
though, and I think we can say

00:51:29.684 --> 00:51:31.768
for sure, and this is where I'll
end today.

00:51:31.768 --> 00:51:35.855
Jesus, himself,
I believe, never saw himself as

00:51:35.855 --> 00:51:38.518
the founder of Christianity.
 

00:51:38.518 --> 00:51:43.110
He didn't think about himself
as starting a new religion.

00:51:43.110 --> 00:51:47.501
I believe he saw himself as
preparing the people of Israel

00:51:47.501 --> 00:51:51.815
to make them ready for the
apocalyptic in-breaking of God

00:51:51.815 --> 00:51:55.130
that was to happen at the end of
time,

00:51:55.130 --> 00:51:58.858
or at the end of our time,
and the setting up of a new

00:51:58.858 --> 00:52:02.346
time of the Kingdom of God,
the Kingdom of Israel that

00:52:02.346 --> 00:52:04.199
would incorporate the whole
world.

00:52:04.199 --> 00:52:08.253
The way I would do this is
Jesus was an apocalyptic Jewish

00:52:08.253 --> 00:52:12.518
prophet who was executed because
the Romans at least believed

00:52:12.518 --> 00:52:16.784
that he or his disciples were
making dangerous claims that he

00:52:16.784 --> 00:52:18.989
was the King of the Jews.
 

00:52:18.989 --> 00:52:21.980
That's all you get on the
historical Jesus,

00:52:21.980 --> 00:52:22.550
sorry.
 

00:52:22.550 --> 00:52:25.039
Next time we start on Paul.
 

00:52:25.039 --> 00:52:27.690
See you next time.
 

